text: An amazing opportunity to visit with US troops serving along the DMZ in Korea yesterday. Name: Brownley, Julia
text:
Community-Based Adult Services (CBAS) are essential for veterans, seniors, and low-income individuals. Unfortunately ‚Äì but not unsurprisingly ‚Äì the proposed Republican budget threatens to gut Medicaid, leading to devastating cuts that could drastically reduce services or even close CBAS centers across the country, including Oxnard Family Circle.

During my recent visit to Oxnard Family Circle, I saw the faces of those who would be directly impacted by these cuts. The center plays a critical role in empowering seniors through care management, adult day health services, and veteran-specific care. I spoke with Oxnard Family Circle's dedicated staff and met many of their program participants. This visit underscored just how vital these services are to the lives of our seniors.

I will keep fighting to protect Medicaid and safeguard these essential programs. Our seniors, veterans, and families deserve better than reckless cuts that threaten their health and well-being.

Name: Lee, Mike
text:
I enjoyed the opportunity to visit Denmark, Estonia, and Finland with my friend, @SenRickScott. Our meetings with government, military, and shipbuilding industry leaders, including Ministers of Defense, Ministers of Foreign Affairs, and legislators were productive. I walk away from this trip with a deeper understanding of the issues facing the region, as well as the regulatory burdens shipbuilders face. While abroad, I also had the distinct privilege to meet with U.S. service members, including one Utahn, at Tapa Army Base in Estonia, to discuss the Baltic region.

The nations I visited are United States allies who have made good on their commitments and have a shared focus on enhancing regional partnerships for shipbuilding and national security. It was an honor to represent Utah overseas, and upon returning home, it is clear to me that the United States is once again respected on the world stage.

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text:
2/ First, just know that MAGA has given up on democracy. Wish it weren't true but it is. They would rather MAGA rule forever than run a fair election where a Democrat might win.

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text:

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text:
4/ The modern, time-tested way to destroy a democracy is NOT a coup or burning down the Parliament or a public confrontation with the judiciary.

It's a slow methodical campaign to weaken the structures of accountability necessary for the political opposition to win elections.

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text:
5/ ELEMENT 1: The Legitimization of Political Violence

Every good authoritarian uses the threat of violence to keep critics silent. That's what the Jan. 6 pardons are about. 

Lisa Murkowski's public worries this week about "retaliation" are chilling.

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text:

In free societies, lawyers guard our rights. Despots can more easily trample our rights if the lawyers are silenced. That's why Trump is forcing the big firms to sign effective loyalty oaths.

Name: Murphy, Christopher

Two things happen on university campuses: youth protest and the guarding of objective truth. Neither are allowed in an autocracy. Thus, Trump's illegal campaign to force campuses to crush dissent.
https://t.co/NGxXae43pB

text:

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text:

https://t.co/RLNtmJ77HE

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text:
12/ They just have to be weakened enough so the tools of accountability don't work anymore.

The press can't tell enough truth. The lawyers won't protect our rights. Campus protest disappears. Opposition funding dries up.

We still have elections. But the regime always wins.

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text:
11/ This is all happening so fast it's hard for the public to see it all as part of one plan. But it is.

And the press, lawyers, colleges and opposition political groups don't have to be DESTROYED in order for this plan to work.

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text: 14/ Second, through mass mobilization. When hundreds of thousands of people rally against this kind of assault on democracy, history shows it works. There is a strange, magic power to mass activation which makes supporters of the regime start to jump ship.

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text:
13/ How do we stop it? 

First, though solidarity. Each set of institutions can't let the regime pick one off from each others. The legal profession failed miserably at this this, but the universities can model a collective strategy to fight back and win.

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text: 16/ I believe those three steps, taken together, will arrest Trump's assault. But if it doesn't, then civil disobedience.  And this conversation will need to happen sooner than we would like. We still have the power, but we have less time than most think.

Name: Murphy, Christopher
text:
15/ Third, through risk taking by political leaders. No citizen will take the risk to mobilize if leaders are playing it safe. 

This means speaking daily truth to the regime and taking tactical risks (like voting against the CR or boycotting the SOTU would have been).

Roy asked then-FBI Director Christopher Wray in July 2023 why FBI Agent Brian Auten was able to suppress the Hunter Biden laptop investigation and participate in the Mar-a-Lago investigation despite being under "disciplinary review" for deceiving FISA courts with the Steele Dossier to spy on the Trump campaign. 

Rep. Roy: "The FBI conducted an internal investigation of Brian Auten and then sought to suspend him but Auten appealed. 

Nevertheless, in 2020, after Senators Grassley and Johnson highlighted evidence of potential financial crimes and corruption against the Biden family, the FBI assigned Auten to compile an assessment, which was used to characterize the Biden revelations as Russian disinformation.  

The evidence Grassley and Johnson had collected was mostly financial records and could easily have been corroborated as authentic. 

And by then, the FBI had the Hunter laptop in its possession for over a year, so it knew the lucrative payments to the Bidens from corrupt anti-American regimes were authentic. 

How on earth did the FBI empower an agent under investigation for potentially corrupt performance and abuse of FISA in one politically fraught investigation, a Democrat operative-driven case against President Trump, to play a key role to undermine a second politically fraught investigation, a case against the Bidens?

Name: Keating, William R.
text:
There is no excuse for how the M√©ndez family is being treated - they deserve answers, they deserve to be reunited, and they certainly should not live under the threat of their husband and father facing deportation to a country that the United States has already recognized as unsafe for them to return to.
 
New Bedford's immigrant community has been a stepping-stone to success for new and first-generation Americans for hundreds of years. Name: Graham, Lindsey
text:
I‚Äôm very pleased to hear that the Supreme Court will review President Trump‚Äôs executive order to end the abuses of birthright citizenship.

I have long believed that the 14th amendment does not require granting citizenship to the children of illegal aliens or foreign nationals here on temporary, nonimmigrant visas. To that end, last year I introduced legislation to limit birthright citizenship.

One of the greatest pull factors for illegal immigration is birthright citizenship. In addition, birth tourism, particularly involving China, is a large industry where people obtain tourist visas for the purpose of giving birth in the U.S. and establishing U.S. citizenship for that child. It is far past time for the United States to recognize the original, constitutional definition of birthright citizenship, as the current practice is being abused in so many ways.

It is my hope the Court will settle this issue once and for all, and that my legislation to stop the abuse of birthright citizenship will pass quickly.

Name: Golden, Jared F.
text:
I appreciate the President's willingness to address the longstanding mismanagement of America's fisheries. Today's executive order covers the exact points I wrote to the administration about last week ‚Äî and have been fighting to fix for the last six years in Congress.

My letter to the administration explained how overregulation and inconsistent rulemaking ‚Äî based on incomplete studies, no less ‚Äî stifles investment in our fisheries and could ultimately decimate the industry. That costs money, jobs, and even food security. And it's already happening in Maine.

Washington has failed our coastal communities by leaving them out of meaningful conversations on offshore energy development, right whale regulations, and more. I'm committed to working with the President to develop a system that finally gives the fishing industry an equal seat at the table. I'm also eager to help tackle the unfair regulatory and trade practices Canada uses to disadvantage American fishermen. 

Maine fishermen have never backed down from these existential fights, and I've always stood with them. Today's executive order is hopefully the first of many new wins for our coastal communities.

text:
Friday in the First

Joan Robinson, a proud Warren County native and longtime resident of Henderson, has spent over 30 years helping young people succeed. As a workforce development and community engagement professional at the Kittrell Job Corps Center, she has helped countless students gain job skills, education, and leadership experience.

Joan also serves as the vice president of the Henderson Optimist Club and holds leadership roles on several community boards, including the Henderson-Vance Chamber of Commerce, the Vance County Arts Council Board, the Perry Memorial Library Board, and the Vance County School Advisory Board.

She has received national and local awards for her leadership and service, including multiple prestigious awards from the National Job Corps Association.¬† Her work has brought people together, built stronger regional connections, and helped prepare the next generation for success.

Name: Houlahan, Chrissy
text:
Law(less) + (Dis)Order(ly) Episode 10

None of these actions make our country safer or citizens more prosperous, but here are some of the things the Trump administration delivered this week:

President Trump is openly defying the United States Supreme Court, refusing to return Kilmar Abrego Garcia to the United States while also threatening to send US citizens to foreign prisons.

President Trump launched Truth Social investment accounts made up of stocks in companies directly benefiting from his tariff and trade policies.

After not updating its tracking website for nearly a month, DOGE removed hundreds of "cuts" they had taken credit for and edited others to try to juice the savings they are claiming.

Sensitive national security information continues to flow out of the Secretary of Defense's office, and multiple political appointees and staffers were escorted out of the Pentagon or placed on administrative leave. Meanwhile, their boss--a chief Signalgate leaker himself--remains uninvestigated and clearly incapable of protecting national secrets.

Trump's choice to lead the IRS had a great week--the nominee had $130K in personal debt paid off by donors who happen to work in tax consulting businesses or are involved in tax-related legal fights.

The Pentagon continued its erasure campaign, this time removing information from its websites about the Air Force's first female Thunderbird pilot and her accomplishments.

The NIH is following suit, as we learned that 38 of the 43 scientists cut from the boards tasked with reviewing science and research happening in NIH laboratories were female, Black or Hispanic.

The federal office responsible for battling foreign disinformation is being eliminated.

E.coli is back! Fifteen states were hit with a deadly outbreak linked to lettuce but the FDA chose not to share this with the American public. Also this week we learned the FDA plans to stop routine food safety inspections.

To be continued...

Its continued renewal highlights the federal government‚Äôs commitment to meeting the evolving needs of the autism community.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we honor members of our community whose strength, compassion, and resilience make a lasting impact. Today, we recognize a family whose faith carried them through the unimaginable‚Äîand who have turned that journey into a mission to serve others. Meet this week‚Äôs Hometown Hero: the Masciantonio family of Warrington.
 
Shortly after Gianna Grace Masciantonio was born, her parents, Joe and Kristen, were told she had only weeks to live. An inoperable tumor had wrapped around her brainstem‚Äîaggressive, untreatable, and fatal. With no options left, they turned to the only thing they had‚Äîfaith. And on Christmas Eve, their prayers were answered. A call from a specialist brought a new possibility: the tumor might not be cancer. A biopsy confirmed it‚ÄîGianna had a rare blood disorder known as systemic JXG. The road ahead would be grueling‚Äî20 surgeries, intense chemotherapy, and months in the hospital‚Äîbut their faith held firm.
 
It was their faith that gave them strength through surgeries and long hospital stays, and it was faith that brought them to Philadelphia in 2015 to be near Pope Francis as he visited the city for the World Family. In a moment neither planned nor imagined, Gianna was lifted into the arms of the Holy Father and kissed on the head. For the Masciantonios, it wasn‚Äôt just a blessing but a sign they were not walking this road alone.
 
Today, Gianna is a thriving 10-year-old with a heart as big as her smile. She loves art, baking, horseback riding, and time spent with her cousins and classmates. But more than anything, she loves life. Every moment with her is a reminder of how precious and miraculous each day truly is. And her parents‚ÄîJoe and Kristen‚Äîhave taken their family‚Äôs deepest pain and turned it into a mission of purpose.
 
After enduring unimaginable challenges, they made a promise to help other families facing similar battles with rare and life-threatening pediatric illnesses. This promise led to the creation of the For the Love of Grace Foundation‚Äîa nonprofit organization grounded in faith, compassion, and action. Since its founding, For the Love of Grace has donated nearly $100,000 to the Children's Hospital of Philadelphia and provided life-changing support to countless local families. Their assistance includes covering medical bills, funding essential home modifications, and creating prayer groups for parents seeking strength and connection. Their motto, Faith Over Fear, is more than just a phrase; it embodies how they live, lead, and uplift others.  
 
As Co-Chair of the Congressional Rare Disease Caucus, I am humbled to work alongside families like the Masciantonios. Their courage is our call to action‚Äîto secure more funding, research, and resources for children and families fighting rare diseases.
 
Joe, Kristen, and Gianna Grace‚Äîyour faith, strength, and generosity have illuminated the way for countless individuals and continue to make a difference in our community and beyond. Thank you for reminding us that even in the darkest times, faith triumphs over fear‚Äîyou are true hometown heroes, and we are grateful for you!

Today we mark 250 years since the Battles of Lexington and Concord‚Äî ‚ÄúThe shot heard round the world.‚Äù

People busy with jobs and families‚Äîworking people, farmers, blacksmiths, and tradesmen‚Äîdecided they would risk it all for freedom.

Their stand wasn‚Äôt just against a king; it was for the radical idea that government should answer to the people.

That idea is under pressure today. We honor their legacy not just by remembering their bravery, but by continuing their struggle ‚Äîevery day‚Äî defending democracy, standing up for what‚Äôs right and making sure that every American has a real say in the future we build together.

Name: Trahan, Lori
text:
250 years ago, right here at the Old North Bridge, ordinary people faced an extraordinary choice: monarchy or democracy. They could remain subjects of a distant crown ‚Äì or risk everything for the idea of self-government.

They chose freedom.

Farmers and blacksmiths, shopkeepers and ministers, teachers and mothers ‚Äì everyday citizens who had no guarantee of success ‚Äì stood their ground. And when the smoke cleared on that April morning, the first shots of a revolution had been fired.

What began here in Concord became ‚Äúthe shot heard round the world.‚Äù It was more than the beginning of a battle ‚Äì it was the beginning of an idea.

That liberty is worth defending. That government derives its just powers from the consent of the governed. That even the smallest towns in the smallest colonies could stir the conscience of a world.

But it was never inevitable.

The men and women who gathered here were not professional soldiers or political elites. They were neighbors and parents. Workers and worshippers. People with families to protect, farms to tend, and lives to live. And yet, when the moment came, they answered history‚Äôs call.

Today, as we mark the 250th anniversary of that defining moment, we gather not just to honor their courage ‚Äì but to reckon with the responsibility they left us.

Name: Cole, Tom
text:
On April 19, 1995, an awful act of domestic terrorism occurred at the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building in Oklahoma City. Today, thirty years later, we remember the 168 precious lives that were brutally taken from us that day and pray for those who still mourn a loved one whose days were cut short.
 
As I reflect on this tragic day, I will also never forget the way our state responded to this horrific event. Oklahoma was launched onto the worldwide stage without any warning. Yet, we responded so strongly, swiftly, and compassionately ‚Äì one of the many reasons I am proud to be an Oklahoman.
 
In conclusion, today, on the 30th anniversary of the Oklahoma City Bombing, we mourn the innocent lives that were prematurely taken from us, grieve with those who lost a loved one on that heartbreaking day, thank our first responders and governing officials who responded so honorably, and stand strong with our fellow Oklahomans. They will not be forgotten.

I first visited the region in 1994 on a study scholarship to Syria & Jordan and have worked in nearly every country in the area. I continue to be impressed and appreciative of the men and women who serve our country in the multi-front effort to reduce the threat of radical Islamic terrorists. While ISIS/Al Qaeda threats continue to be significant, our most pressing issue is to suppress and roll back the many nefarious tentacles of Iranian backed militants spreading instability and death. While America must deal with the realities of rising threats from China and the Pacific rim, we must do so in a way that better leverages our security partners in the Middle East and is not naive to the realities and dangers of the region. üá∫üá∏

I had the honor of welcoming to Concord two women whose lives and work have not only shaped how we understand our history but are actively influencing the future of our democracy: @DorisKGoodwin, a longtime Concord resident and one of our nation‚Äôs most gifted historians, and @RosieRios, the 43rd Treasurer of the United States.

Though now to Death I yield, and am his due
All that of me can die, yet that debt paid,
Thou wilt not leave me in the loathsom grave
His prey, nor suffer my unspotted Soule
For ever with corruption there to dwell;
But I shall rise Victorious, and subdue
My Vanquisher, spoild of his vanted spoile;
Death his deaths wound shall then receive, and stoop
Inglorious, of his mortal sting disarm'd.
I through the ample Air in Triumph high
Shall lead Hell Captive maugre Hell, and show
The powers of darkness bound. Thou at the sight
Pleas'd, out of Heaven shalt look down and smile,
While by thee rais'd I ruin all my Foes,
Death last, and with his Carcass glut the Grave:
Then with the multitude of my redeemd
Shall enter Heaven long absent, and returne,
Father, to see thy face, wherein no cloud
Of anger shall remain, but peace assur'd,
And reconcilement; wrauth shall be no more
Thenceforth, but in thy presence Joy entire.‚Äù
- Paradise Lost, Book 3

Name: Trahan, Lori
text:
I join the millions of people around the world mourning the passing of Pope Francis, a transformational leader whose humility, compassion, and moral clarity touched the lives of so many.

Born in Argentina to an immigrant family, Pope Francis brought a unique and powerful perspective to the papacy ‚Äî one grounded in empathy for the marginalized and a deep understanding of the struggles facing ordinary people. His decision to become the first pope to choose St. Francis of Assisi as his papal namesake was a profound reflection of his commitment to humility, peace, and care for the poor, values that guided every step of his leadership.

Whether advocating for the most vulnerable, calling on global leaders to act on climate change, or urging the Church to be a more welcoming place for all, Pope Francis led with a spirit of love and service. His legacy will endure in the countless lives he uplifted and the hope he brought to those who have too often felt unseen.

May he rest in peace.

Name: Garcia, Sylvia R.
text:
I join millions around the world in mourning the passing of Pope Francis. 

His papacy will be remembered for its compassion, its moral clarity, and a renewed belief that we are all God‚Äôs children.

As the first Jesuit pope, he challenged the wealthy and the powerful to see dignity in the faces of the migrant, the worker, the child. 

He stood in refugee camps in Lampedusa. He walked the dusty roads of forgotten villages. He brought light and joy to those long cast in shadow.

More than any Pope before, he urged us to care for our common home, reminding us that caring for the Earth is not optional‚Äîit is a moral and spiritual obligation.¬†

When the world felt uncertain, he offered steadiness. God sent us a good man in Pope Francis. A shepherd. A servant. A son of the Americas who became beloved across the world.¬†

I and millions around the globe will miss his wisdom, gentleness, and quiet strength he carried in every word and every step. May he rest in peace, and may we all carry his light forward.

Name: Pelosi, Nancy
text:
It is with immense sadness that Paul and I join our fellow Catholics and people of faith around the world in mourning the loss of His Holiness Pope Francis: a beacon of charity, hope and love for all people of faith.¬†He rekindled the faith of Catholics worldwide, with a triumphant message of peace that has inspired a generation.¬†

Pope Francis personified our sacred responsibility in the Gospel of Matthew to honor the spark of divinity in the least of our brethren ‚Äî championing the poor, the worker, the refugee and the immigrant.¬†He reminded us of our inescapable duty to those struggling to escape poverty and persecution in our communities and around the world.¬† 

Perhaps his most distinctive leadership will be his historic commitment to addressing the climate crisis.¬†In his ground-breaking encyclical,¬†Laudato Si, Pope Francis writes with beauty and clarity, with moral force and fierce urgency to call on all of us to be good stewards of God‚Äôs Creation.

Personally, the loss of Pope Francis is devastating.¬† It was my high honor to attend his installation on the Feast of Saint Joseph in 2013 and to be in the House chamber during his historic address to the Congress in 2015.¬†

In San Francisco, we take special pride in Pope Francis, as he shares the namesake of our City and honors the call of our anthem, the Song of Saint Francis, to be an ‚Äòinstrument of peace.‚Äô

Many of us who met His Holiness know that he would always say, ‚ÄúPray for me.‚Äù¬† Now, we will pray to him and pledge to carry on his towering legacy.¬† May he rest in peace.

In 2019, a federal immigration judge granted him ‚Äúwithholding from removal‚Äù status, which protects him from being deported to El Salvador.

He was sent to El Salvador anyway ‚Äì a mistake this administration called an ‚Äúadministrative error.‚Äù

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
On March 15, Trump Administration officials sent Abrego Garcia to El Salvador‚Äôs maximum-security prison for his alleged ties to the MS-13 gang ‚Äì without any evidence to support this claim, and without bringing his case before a judge.

He‚Äôs a husband and a father who was in the first year of a sheet metal apprenticeship, actively contributing to our economy and working to rebuild our country. He was in a union, not a gang.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
In a unanimous ruling on April 10, the Supreme Court ordered the Trump Administration to ‚Äúfacilitate‚Äù Abrego Garcia‚Äôs return to the U.S.

On the visit to the White House, the President of El Salvador said he wouldn‚Äôt release Abrego Garcia. The Trump Administration hasn‚Äôt asked for him to be released and hasn‚Äôt shared any other attempts to bring him home ‚Äì things they could easily do.

Name: Kennedy, John

Social Security is a promise to the American people ‚Äî a promise that after a lifetime of hard work, you can retire with dignity. It‚Äôs a promise that our veterans will be cared for, that people with disabilities won‚Äôt be left behind, and that working families will have some stability in an unstable world.

More than 70 million Americans ‚Äì including over 136,000 in Ventura County and the Conejo Valley ‚Äì rely on Social Security every single day. It‚Äôs how they pay rent, how they buy groceries and prescriptions, and how they stay afloat.

Without Social Security, one in three Americans would be pushed into poverty. This program is not a handout. It‚Äôs a lifeline. That is why I will never stop fighting to protect Social Security and uphold the promise we‚Äôve made to everyone who depends on it.

text:

text:
Circumstances have dramatically changed since then.
¬†
Today, we have a President who is gutting critical environmental and public health protections and prioritizing the profits of corporate polluters.

text:

text:

text:

text:
President Trump and Republicans have said that caring about our planet is part of so-called ‚Äúculture wars.‚Äù

Name: Smith, Adam
text:
Today, a mass shooting in Kashmir killed at least two dozen people and injured many more. This is one of the worst attacks this region has seen in years, and I condemn this brutal attack against civilians.

My heartfelt condolences go out to the Indian people and the families who have lost loved ones from this violent attack. I hope for a speedy recovery for all those who were injured, and that the perpetrators are held accountable. The U.S. stands with India in the global fight against terrorism.
